1
00:00:01,786 --> 00:00:31,303
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:32,042 --> 00:00:35,646
I've forgotten to put my microphone on, so I shall do that now.

3
00:00:35,686 --> 00:00:46,497
Okay.

4
00:00:48,880 --> 00:01:00,631
So, I've chosen the victory verses of the Buddha to end my little five efforts at the Dhammapada.

5
00:01:01,658 --> 00:01:03,500
So, I shall chant it.

6
00:01:03,521 --> 00:01:06,344
This is the one I know, by the way, because we do it every morning.

7
00:01:06,364 --> 00:01:28,459
āne kājāti saṃsāraṃ saṅdāve saṅga nībhīsaṃ gāhākārākā gāve saṅto duḥkājāti puṇā puṇāṃ gāhākārākā dito zi puṇā gihāṃ nā kaha zi

8
00:01:28,658 --> 00:01:44,441
So the translation.

9
00:01:44,501 --> 00:01:51,972
Through many rounds of rebirth have I wandered, looking for the house builder, but not finding him.

10
00:01:52,513 --> 00:01:54,415
Painful is repeated rebirth.

11
00:01:55,457 --> 00:01:57,501
O house builder, you are seen.

12
00:01:57,868 --> 00:01:59,671
You will not build this house again.

13
00:02:00,290 --> 00:02:01,852
All your rafters are broken.

14
00:02:01,912 --> 00:02:03,875
The ridge pole is destroyed.

15
00:02:04,915 --> 00:02:10,562
My citta is not conditioned and I have attained the end of all cravings.

16
00:02:11,742 --> 00:02:14,885
So I just want to go through this, the Pali there.

17
00:02:14,945 --> 00:02:20,231
The word for wander also means to sort of run.

18
00:02:21,173 --> 00:02:26,457
So a word like coursing through rebirth after rebirth.

19
00:02:26,810 --> 00:02:30,294
I think it gives the idea of that onward going samsara.

20
00:02:33,258 --> 00:02:40,788
There's a lovely little word, aneka, which it translates as not one, therefore it means many.

21
00:02:41,688 --> 00:02:44,451
It's just a nice way of saying it, not one.

22
00:02:48,737 --> 00:02:53,644
There's not much there to, that's the first verse.

23
00:02:53,758 --> 00:03:01,689
Now, of course, these are called the victory verses of the Buddha, which there's some idea that he spoke them after his awakening.

24
00:03:01,710 --> 00:03:06,096
But I dare say he manufactured them, shall we say.

25
00:03:06,116 --> 00:03:12,506
He created them sometime afterwards to express what his kernel insight was.

26
00:03:12,966 --> 00:03:14,247
And we shall come to that.

27
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:24,229
So now the house builder, you have seen, you have been discovered, you have been uncovered.

28
00:03:25,091 --> 00:03:26,772
You'll not build a house for me again.

29
00:03:27,114 --> 00:03:28,656
Your rafters are broken.

30
00:03:29,235 --> 00:03:33,080
Now the word for rafter is also the word for rib, so that makes sense.

31
00:03:35,003 --> 00:03:41,771
The ridge pole, the top of the roof is destroyed, and that's basically what the Pali says, the top of the roof.

32
00:03:43,252 --> 00:03:57,651
Now, the citta is translated usually as mind, but obviously it can't be part of the candor, part of the aggregates, because it's not conditioned.

33
00:03:57,832 --> 00:04:12,331
The aggregates, which are of course your physicality, your feelings, all your perceptions, concepts, all your habits and momentary consciousnesses that manifest these things,

34
00:04:12,312 --> 00:04:25,983
are all conditioned now the word here is vi sankara so v is another way of saying not and the word there is sankara right so it's not conditioned

35
00:04:30,048 --> 00:04:51,112
And then the last verse is tanha, is again this destruction of this wrong desire based on the delusion of the house builder, which of course manifests as greed, aversion, and fear as a basic relationship to the world we live in.

36
00:04:53,413 --> 00:04:55,937
So that's the verses.

37
00:05:00,456 --> 00:05:08,350
Now, normally speaking, this would evoke then the life of the Buddha, how he became fully liberated, etc., etc.

38
00:05:08,391 --> 00:05:09,773
But I think most of you know that.

39
00:05:10,615 --> 00:05:22,194
And there's this quite amazing little discourse from the Sanyuttanikaya, the gradual sayings, they're the small discourses.

40
00:05:23,086 --> 00:05:25,552
and it's called With Kaimaka.

41
00:05:25,574 --> 00:05:27,680
So it's about this senior monk.

42
00:05:28,281 --> 00:05:31,711
So I'm going to read it, take some time over it, because it's quite delightful.

43
00:05:33,312 --> 00:05:39,762
At one time several senior mendicants or monks were staying near Kosambi at Gosita's monastery.

44
00:05:40,041 --> 00:05:48,555
Now at the time the Venerable Kemaka was staying at the Jujube tree monastery and he was sick, suffering, gravely ill.

45
00:05:49,336 --> 00:05:56,146
In the late afternoon these senior mendicants came out of retreat and addressed the Venerable Dasaka.

46
00:05:56,127 --> 00:06:05,723
Please, Venerable Dasaka, go to the mendicant Kaimaka and say to him, Reverend Kaimaka, the seniors hope you are keeping well.

47
00:06:06,144 --> 00:06:07,848
They hope you are all right.

48
00:06:08,329 --> 00:06:10,932
They hope your pain is fading, not growing.

49
00:06:11,374 --> 00:06:15,721
That it's fading is evident, not it's growing.

50
00:06:15,786 --> 00:06:22,154
So Deska wanders off and I presume it's quite a way because he's living in another monastery.

51
00:06:22,634 --> 00:06:26,680
It would have been close by, but at least he's got to go over and find him.

52
00:06:27,360 --> 00:06:35,550
And when, of course, he gets to Kemeka and relates this to him, Kemeka says, no, he said, I'm not all right.

53
00:06:35,690 --> 00:06:38,615
My pain is terrible and growing, not fading.

54
00:06:39,194 --> 00:06:42,199
And his growing is evident and it's not fading.

55
00:06:42,853 --> 00:06:47,362
So Daska then goes all the way back to the seniors and the seniors say,

56
00:06:49,199 --> 00:07:00,074
Ask him, say, Reverend Kemaka, the seniors say that these five grasping aggregates, so actually five khanda, have been taught by the Buddha.

57
00:07:00,173 --> 00:07:05,422
That is, the grasping aggregate of form, feeling, perception.

58
00:07:06,081 --> 00:07:18,699
It's got, and here's a translation from the Sutta Central, which is Sujata's, Sujato's, Sujato's,

59
00:07:19,269 --> 00:07:49,242
website where he's translated all the discourses he's translated sankara here as choices right no habits not volitional condition but choices i thought was rather nice and consciousness do you regard any of these five aggregates as self or as belonging to self anyway off das dasika goes and uh he asks uh chemical this and um he says uh

60
00:07:52,074 --> 00:08:14,622
the grasp hold on all right and then he says now concerned this is this i do not regard anything among the five grasping aggregates as self or as belonging to herself so vendor bodaska goes back and he tells the seniors and then the seniors say

61
00:08:17,235 --> 00:08:24,526
That is, you know, because he does not see them as self or belonging to herself.

62
00:08:25,629 --> 00:08:39,249
If, as it seems, Venerable Kamaka does not regard anything among these five grasping aggregates as belonging to herself or herself, then he is a perfected one with defilements ended.

63
00:08:39,288 --> 00:08:40,650
In other words, he's an Arahant.

64
00:08:41,572 --> 00:08:44,998
So off he goes, Desika, to see...

65
00:08:46,496 --> 00:09:10,833
see his poor chemical who's suffering i mean he's in pain and uh he said he says no i do not regard anything among these five aggregates belonging yourself yet i am not a perfected one with defilements ended for when it comes to the five grasping aggregates i'm not rid of the conceit of i am

66
00:09:11,842 --> 00:09:15,913
but I don't regard anything as I am this.

67
00:09:19,081 --> 00:09:26,341
So off he goes, Daska goes back to the seniors on the other side of the fence.

68
00:09:27,149 --> 00:09:28,673
And the seniors send him off again.

69
00:09:29,475 --> 00:09:37,575
So the seniors say, the message this time to K. Makar is, when you say I am, what is it that you're talking about?

70
00:09:38,115 --> 00:09:40,360
Is it the form or apart from form?

71
00:09:40,381 --> 00:09:41,865
Is it feeling, perception?

72
00:09:42,706 --> 00:09:44,652
What is it you're talking about?

73
00:09:47,230 --> 00:09:54,616
So Venerable Kemaka now gets fed up with this and he says, what's the point of running back and forth?

74
00:09:54,778 --> 00:10:00,182
Bring me my staff and I'll go and see these senior mendicants myself.

75
00:10:00,202 --> 00:10:01,004
So off he goes.

76
00:10:01,684 --> 00:10:05,327
And when he arrives, of course, the usual exchanging of greetings.

77
00:10:06,389 --> 00:10:07,931
And then he sat down to one side.

78
00:10:07,990 --> 00:10:13,996
So they say to him, when you say I am, what is it you're talking about?

79
00:10:16,035 --> 00:10:40,996
uh venerables i don't say i am with reference to form or apart from form and that's the same for feeling perception choices sankara consciousness and consciousness but when it comes to the five aggregates i'm not rid of the conceit i am but i don't regard anything as i am this

80
00:10:41,298 --> 00:11:03,205
then he gives this simile it's like the scent of a blue water lily or a pink one or a white Lotus would it be right to say the scent belongs to the petals or the stalk or the pistil no Reverend then reverence how should it be said it would be right to say the scent belongs to the flower

81
00:11:04,282 --> 00:11:14,517
In the same way, reverends, I don't say with reference to form or apart from form, I don't say I am.

82
00:11:15,217 --> 00:11:22,067
The same with feeling, perception, conditional volitionings or choices, and consciousness.

83
00:11:23,409 --> 00:11:30,659
For when it comes to the five grasping aggregates, I am not rid of the conceit I am.

84
00:11:30,893 --> 00:11:34,515
but I don't regard anything as I am this.

85
00:11:37,798 --> 00:11:53,052
Although a noble disciple has given up the five lower fetters, they still have a lingering residue of the conceit I am, the desire I am, and the underlying tendency I am, which has not been eradicated.

86
00:11:53,673 --> 00:11:59,398
Now, the five lower fetters go with sotapanna, the stream entrant.

87
00:11:59,529 --> 00:12:22,298
something's broken but not this sense of self after some time they meditate observing the rise and fall of the five grasping aggregates such is form such is the origin of form such is the end of form and the same with feeling perception choices and consciousness

88
00:12:23,745 --> 00:12:30,712
And as they do so, the lingering residue is eradicated.

89
00:12:31,833 --> 00:12:35,077
And then he gives another simile.

90
00:12:35,938 --> 00:12:42,365
Suppose there was a cloth that was dirty and soiled, so the owners gave it to a launderer.

91
00:12:43,285 --> 00:12:51,475
The launderer kneads it thoroughly with salt, lye, and cow dung, and rinses it in clear water.

92
00:12:51,961 --> 00:13:15,183
although that cloth is clean and bright it still has a lingering scent of salt lye and cow dung that has not been eradicated the launderer returns it to the owners who store it in a chest permeated with scent and the lingering scent would be eradicated

93
00:13:15,956 --> 00:13:38,758
in the same way although a noble disciple has given up the five lower fetters they still have a lingering residue of the conceit i am the desire i am and the underlying tendency i am which has not been eradicated and after some time etc etc

94
00:13:39,211 --> 00:13:42,114
The lingering residue is eradicated.

95
00:13:42,934 --> 00:14:01,615
Now, when he said this, the senior mendicant said to Venerable Kaimaka, we didn't want to trouble you with our questions, but you're capable of explaining, teaching, advocating, establishing, disclosing, analyzing, and clarifying the Buddha's instructions in detail.

96
00:14:02,235 --> 00:14:04,138
And that's just what you've done.

97
00:14:05,148 --> 00:14:07,169
That's what Venerable Kaimaka said.

98
00:14:07,509 --> 00:14:12,755
Satisfied, the senior bhikkhus were happy with what Venerable Kaimaka said.

99
00:14:13,355 --> 00:14:26,129
And while this discourse was being spoken, the minds of 60 senior bhikkhus and of the Venerable Kaimaka were freed from defilements by non grasping.

100
00:14:26,149 --> 00:14:28,351
So they all became fully liberated.

101
00:14:30,013 --> 00:14:31,695
Now,

102
00:14:32,889 --> 00:14:40,091
The distinction here is between a view of self and a sense of self.

103
00:14:40,110 --> 00:14:47,052
One incident that comes to mind is concerning smoking.

104
00:14:48,971 --> 00:14:54,018
You know, there was a time when smoking was not thought to be particularly harmful.

105
00:14:54,778 --> 00:15:04,009
And then during the 50s, especially as I remember, 50s and 60s, it slowly became apparent that in fact it caused things like cancer, lung cancer.

106
00:15:04,629 --> 00:15:12,820
And of course, there was the usual effort by the tobacco companies and any company to protect itself with false science and fake news.

107
00:15:13,120 --> 00:15:22,936
But when it finally came through, the science did come through, then people became convinced that smoking actually caused cancer and death.

108
00:15:24,038 --> 00:15:33,673
Now, even though the view of the smoker was changed from being non-harmful to being harmful, did they stop smoking?

109
00:15:35,296 --> 00:15:36,057
No.

110
00:15:36,289 --> 00:16:01,335
so here even though the view of a self seeing this psychophysical organism as me is broken with the stream entrance still there lingers on this idea of me and it's an underlying tendency so it's got it's very deeply ingrained and that me remember is the way that this

111
00:16:01,687 --> 00:16:11,080
Awareness, this satipanya, this intuitive awareness, the Buddha within, experiences itself within the five khandhas.

112
00:16:12,061 --> 00:16:17,869
That's the sense of self you get when you become the observer, the feeler, the knower.

113
00:16:18,509 --> 00:16:23,897
And of course, you can't get rid of that by an act of will.

114
00:16:24,282 --> 00:16:43,354
But what Kemaka is saying, and what he's saying that the Buddha said was, you just keep investigating the impermanence of the five khandhas of this organism, and at some point, you'll break through that final delusion and become fully liberated.

115
00:16:43,739 --> 00:16:46,645
So the task in hand is very clear.

116
00:16:46,785 --> 00:16:57,330
We have to keep meditating and not only in meditation, but in ordinary daily life to keep on realizing that everything is arising and passing away.

117
00:16:57,389 --> 00:17:01,899
It has no substance and therefore it's not worth clinging to.

118
00:17:03,618 --> 00:17:16,851
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, that they have not caused greater confusion, and that you will, by your practice, liberate yourself, as Kaimaka did, from all suffering.

